<subSubSection id="C371EBB5FF85FFB74092104A393A0818" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="key">
<key id="FFFAEF0FFF85FFB74092104A393A0818" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<keyStep id="309FA09BFF85FFB74092104A393A0DB7" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF85FFB74092104A393B0DED" blockId="20.[189,1399,337,1146]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF85FFB74092104A393B0DED" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
1. Female: scutellum and clypeus completely ferruginous (
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF85FFB7439F1049386E0D0E" box="[944,1059,337,364]" captionStart="Figs 100–105. 100–101" captionStartId="125.[189,241,1925,1951]" captionTargetBox="[265,1323,265,1893]" captionTargetId="figure-52@125.[265,1323,265,1901]" captionTargetPageId="125" captionText="Figs 100–105. 100–101. Sphex decipiens Kohl, 1895. 102–103. S. pruinosus Germar, 1817. 104– 105. S. gaullei Berland, 1927. 100, 103, 105. Habitus of ♂. 101. Frontal view of ♀. 102, 104. Habitus of ♀." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299470" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6299470/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Figs 104</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF85FFB74418104938E70D0E" box="[1079,1194,337,364]" captionStart="Figs 106–112. 106–107" captionStartId="131.[189,241,1889,1915]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,265,1864]" captionTargetId="figure-79@131.[203,1385,265,1865]" captionTargetPageId="131" captionText="Figs 106–112. 106–107. Sphex jansei Cameron, 1910. 108. S. schmideggeri sp. nov. 109. S. pseudosatanas sp. nov. 110–111. S. rufoclypeatus sp. nov. 106, 108–110. Habitus of ♀. 107, 111. Habitus of ♂. 112. Geographic distribution of S. decipiens Kohl, 1895 (red), S. pruinosus Germar, 1817 (blue), S. gaullei Berland, 1927 (yellow), S. jansei (purple) and S. schmideggeri sp. nov. (green)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299472" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6299472/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">106, 108</figureCitation>
). Male: at least lower/inner third of clypeus ferruginous; facial setae golden or silvery.......................................2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF85FFB740EE1080393A0DB7" blockId="20.[189,1399,337,1146]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF85FFB740EE1080393A0DB7" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
– Female: scutellum and at least upper half of clypeus black (
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF85FFB743D3108038E60DD0" box="[1020,1195,408,434]" captionStart="Figs 100–105. 100–101" captionStartId="125.[189,241,1925,1951]" captionTargetBox="[265,1323,265,1893]" captionTargetId="figure-52@125.[265,1323,265,1901]" captionTargetPageId="125" captionText="Figs 100–105. 100–101. Sphex decipiens Kohl, 1895. 102–103. S. pruinosus Germar, 1817. 104– 105. S. gaullei Berland, 1927. 100, 103, 105. Habitus of ♂. 101. Frontal view of ♀. 102, 104. Habitus of ♀." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299470" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6299470/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Figs 100–102</figureCitation>
). Male: clypeus nearly or completely black; facial setae never golden..................................................................4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="309FA09BFF85FFB74092131C393A0EAC" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF85FFB74092131C393A0E07" blockId="20.[189,1399,337,1146]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF85FFB74092131C393A0E07" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
2. Petiole and metasomal segment I bright ferruginous (
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF85FFB7435C131C3F930E7C" box="[883,990,516,542]" captionStart="Figs 106–112. 106–107" captionStartId="131.[189,241,1889,1915]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,265,1864]" captionTargetId="figure-79@131.[203,1385,265,1865]" captionTargetPageId="131" captionText="Figs 106–112. 106–107. Sphex jansei Cameron, 1910. 108. S. schmideggeri sp. nov. 109. S. pseudosatanas sp. nov. 110–111. S. rufoclypeatus sp. nov. 106, 108–110. Habitus of ♀. 107, 111. Habitus of ♂. 112. Geographic distribution of S. decipiens Kohl, 1895 (red), S. pruinosus Germar, 1817 (blue), S. gaullei Berland, 1927 (yellow), S. jansei (purple) and S. schmideggeri sp. nov. (green)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299472" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6299472/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 108</figureCitation>
). Female: meso- and metapleurae ferruginous; basal half of forewing with conspicuous yellow tinge and cellular wing area not infuscate. Male: erect clypeal and paraocular setae silvery ...... 
<taxonomicName id="4C6BC3BDFF85FFB74413135239490E07" authority="Dörfel &amp; Ohl, 2022" authorityName="Dörfel &amp; Ohl" authorityYear="2022" box="[1084,1284,586,613]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Sphex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schmideggeri" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B91F642CFF85FFB74413135239490E07" bold="true" box="[1084,1284,586,613]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">S. schmideggeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A22CD957FF85FFB7453B1353393A0E07" box="[1300,1399,587,613]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF85FFB740EE1376393A0EAC" blockId="20.[189,1399,337,1146]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF85FFB740EE1376393A0EAC" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
– Petiole and metasoma black (
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF85FFB7426313763EB80EEA" box="[588,757,622,648]" captionStart-0="Figs 100–105. 100–101" captionStart-1="Figs 106–112. 106–107" captionStartId-0="125.[189,241,1925,1951]" captionStartId-1="131.[189,241,1889,1915]" captionTargetBox-0="[265,1323,265,1893]" captionTargetBox-1="[203,1385,265,1864]" captionTargetId-0="figure-52@125.[265,1323,265,1901]" captionTargetId-1="figure-79@131.[203,1385,265,1865]" captionTargetPageId-0="125" captionTargetPageId-1="131" captionText-0="Figs 100–105. 100–101. Sphex decipiens Kohl, 1895. 102–103. S. pruinosus Germar, 1817. 104– 105. S. gaullei Berland, 1927. 100, 103, 105. Habitus of ♂. 101. Frontal view of ♀. 102, 104. Habitus of ♀." captionText-1="Figs 106–112. 106–107. Sphex jansei Cameron, 1910. 108. S. schmideggeri sp. nov. 109. S. pseudosatanas sp. nov. 110–111. S. rufoclypeatus sp. nov. 106, 108–110. Habitus of ♀. 107, 111. Habitus of ♂. 112. Geographic distribution of S. decipiens Kohl, 1895 (red), S. pruinosus Germar, 1817 (blue), S. gaullei Berland, 1927 (yellow), S. jansei (purple) and S. schmideggeri sp. nov. (green)." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299470" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299472" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6299470/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6299472/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Figs 104–107</figureCitation>
). Female: meso- and metapleurae black; cellular area of forewing either hyaline and without yellow tinge or notably infuscate in apical part with at most inconspicuous yellow tinge near wing base. Male: erect clypeal and paraocular setae golden......3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="309FA09BFF85FFB7409213E5393A0FA5" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF85FFB7409213E5393A0F3C" blockId="20.[189,1399,337,1146]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF85FFB7409213E5393A0F3C" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
3. Female: cellular area of forewing hyaline (
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF85FFB742D913E53F1F0F75" box="[758,850,765,791]" captionStart="Figs 25–32. 25–26" captionStartId="21.[189,241,1788,1814]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,265,1761]" captionTargetId="figure-95@21.[189,1399,265,1761]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs 25–32. 25–26. Ventral and lateral view of sternum VIII and genitalia in male of Sphex abyssinicus (Arnold, 1928). 27–28. Frontal view of free clypeal margin in males. 29–32. Dorsal view of fore- and hindwing in males and females of thegaullei group. 27. S. umtalicus Strand, 1916. 28. S. decipiens Kohl, 1895. 29. S. jansei Cameron, 1910, ♀. 30. S. jansei, ♂. 31. S. gaullei Berland, 1927, ♀. 32. S. gaullei, ♂." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6299450/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
), usually without violet iridescence; pronotal lobe predominantly black. Male: hindwing and cellular area of forewing hyaline (
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF85FFB744FA123839620F58" box="[1237,1327,800,826]" captionStart="Figs 25–32. 25–26" captionStartId="21.[189,241,1788,1814]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,265,1761]" captionTargetId="figure-95@21.[189,1399,265,1761]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs 25–32. 25–26. Ventral and lateral view of sternum VIII and genitalia in male of Sphex abyssinicus (Arnold, 1928). 27–28. Frontal view of free clypeal margin in males. 29–32. Dorsal view of fore- and hindwing in males and females of thegaullei group. 27. S. umtalicus Strand, 1916. 28. S. decipiens Kohl, 1895. 29. S. jansei Cameron, 1910, ♀. 30. S. jansei, ♂. 31. S. gaullei Berland, 1927, ♀. 32. S. gaullei, ♂." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6299450/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
) ....... .................................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C6BC3BDFF85FFB74412125B393A0F3C" authority="Cameron, 1910" authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1910" box="[1085,1399,835,862]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Sphex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jansei">
<emphasis id="B91F642CFF85FFB74412125B38E60F3F" bold="true" box="[1085,1195,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">S. jansei</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFFAC5CFFF85FFB74495125C393A0F3C" author="Cameron P." box="[1210,1399,836,862]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="116 - 154" refId="ref129378" refString="Cameron P. 1910. On the aculeate Hymenoptera collected by Mr. A. J. T. Janse, Normal College, Pretoria, in the Transvaal. Annals of the Transvaal Museum 2: 116 - 154." type="journal article" year="1910">Cameron, 1910</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF85FFB740EE127F393A0FA5" blockId="20.[189,1399,337,1146]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF85FFB740EE127F393A0FA5" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
– Female: apical half of forewing markedly infuscate (
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF85FFB74359127F3F9F0FE3" box="[886,978,871,897]" captionStart="Figs 25–32. 25–26" captionStartId="21.[189,241,1788,1814]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,265,1761]" captionTargetId="figure-95@21.[189,1399,265,1761]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs 25–32. 25–26. Ventral and lateral view of sternum VIII and genitalia in male of Sphex abyssinicus (Arnold, 1928). 27–28. Frontal view of free clypeal margin in males. 29–32. Dorsal view of fore- and hindwing in males and females of thegaullei group. 27. S. umtalicus Strand, 1916. 28. S. decipiens Kohl, 1895. 29. S. jansei Cameron, 1910, ♀. 30. S. jansei, ♂. 31. S. gaullei Berland, 1927, ♀. 32. S. gaullei, ♂." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6299450/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
), with violet iridescence; pronotal lobe predominantly ferruginous. Male: cellular area of forewing infuscate in apical half, or at least apical margin of hindwing infuscate (
<figureCitation id="1350A4BBFF85FFB742CA12B53F760FA5" box="[741,827,941,967]" captionStart="Figs 25–32. 25–26" captionStartId="21.[189,241,1788,1814]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,265,1761]" captionTargetId="figure-95@21.[189,1399,265,1761]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs 25–32. 25–26. Ventral and lateral view of sternum VIII and genitalia in male of Sphex abyssinicus (Arnold, 1928). 27–28. Frontal view of free clypeal margin in males. 29–32. Dorsal view of fore- and hindwing in males and females of thegaullei group. 27. S. umtalicus Strand, 1916. 28. S. decipiens Kohl, 1895. 29. S. jansei Cameron, 1910, ♀. 30. S. jansei, ♂. 31. S. gaullei Berland, 1927, ♀. 32. S. gaullei, ♂." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6299450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6299450/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
) .................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C6BC3BDFF85FFB7447B12B5393A0FA5" authority="Berland, 1927" authorityName="Berland" authorityYear="1927" box="[1108,1399,941,968]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Sphex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gaullei">
<emphasis id="B91F642CFF85FFB7447B12B5388A0FAA" bold="true" box="[1108,1223,941,968]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">S. gaullei</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFFAC5CFFF85FFB744E012B5393A0FA5" author="Berland L." box="[1231,1399,941,967]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="150 - 156" refId="ref128862" refString="Berland L. 1927. Les Sphegidae (Hymenopteres) du Museum National de Paris (4 e note). Bulletin du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle 33: 150 - 156." type="journal article" year="1927">Berland, 1927</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="309FA09BFF85FFB7409212EE393A0818" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<paragraph id="8BD4B83EFF85FFB7409212EE393A0851" blockId="20.[189,1399,337,1146]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<keyLead id="309A1B0BFF85FFB7409212EE393A0851" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
